04018nam a22006375i 9781463235789DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20162016nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814632357897 a10.31826/97814632357892doi  a(DE-B1597)505887  a(OCoLC)1100455570  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aREL0490002bisacsh04a616.8/4980093986181 aBarkas, Nikolaos, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSleep and Sleeplessness in Byzantium /cNikolaos Barkas. 1aPiscataway, NJ : bGorgias Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (349 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGorgias Studies in Classical and Late Antiquity00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The mechanics of sleep and sleeplessness -- t3. Sleep-abstinence in the Bible and Hellenic world: An overview -- t4. On Sleep and other demons -- t5. The vigil of monks -- t6. The sleep of laity -- t7. The vigil of the laity -- t8. Conclusions -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent decades certain historians have intimated that Byzantine society - and monastics in particular - suffered from a lack of sleep (whether described in negative terms as sleep deprivation or sleep abstinence). Sleep-abstinence surely permeated Byzantine society: it is encountered in every age, sex and class, together with its institutions, beliefs, practices, rituals, morals and mythologies. However, sleep is a biological phenomenon as well. One cannot possibly appreciate the Byzantines' stance towards it, nor assess the veracity, aims and effectiveness of their ideas and attitudes in relation to sleep-abstinence, unless one is ready to tackle the biological aspect. Moreover, without the biological aspect, the claim that the Byzantines were sleep-deprived is impossible to substantiate. This book approaches this subject by using a bio-cultural method, which combines sleep medicine with theology, history, and critical research, in order to analyse the practice of sleep-abstinence and the attitudes towards sleep in Byzantium. Focusing on Greek documentary sources, this book investigates whether Byzantines did indeed practice sleep abstinence or sleep deprivation, and their rationales for curtailing their sleep. Chapters cover the mechanics of sleep in the modern world and in the ancient world, the place of monastic vigil, and the vigil of the laity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Orthodox.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertGorgias Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066302040uhttps://doi.org/10.31826/978146323578940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781463235789423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781463235789/original  a978-3-11-066302-0  Gorgias Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK